The hist() method relies on Matplotlib, which in turn relies on a user-specified graphical backend to draw on screen
%matplotlib line
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
data.hist(bins=50, figsize=(20,15)
plt.show()

Above uses Jupyter's magic command %matplotlib line which tells Jupyter to set up Matplotlib so it uses Jupyter's own backend

OneHotEncoder converts integer categorical values into one-hot vectors with the output a SciPy sparse matrix. One hot encoding is where to create one binary attribute per category: one attribute equal to 1 when the category is "<1H OCEAN" (and 0 otherwise), another attribute equal to 1 when the category is "NEAR OCEAN" (and 0 otherwise), and so on. This allows only one attribute be equal to 1 (hot) while the others will be 0 (cold).
